Summary of my Work¶

  • I have experiemeted with all models those we have learned in the class.
  • The file takes around 15-20 minutes to process the file.
  • By reading the background, context and after high level overview of the data, predicting that features likes having good monthly income, age, Number of trips taken (shows interest in travel in general) and customer interactive data like 'duration of pitch' are important and influence customer to purchase a new product.
  • Not sure why Owning car and passport are important features. But I will try to learn from the models which i'm going to build about these features. I would keep them than dropping columns. It is my personal experience that many resorts are in driving distance too.
  • I have used feature engineering techniques such as one hot encoding, handled 'Fe Male' in gender (wrongly typed) where they should not be, outlier detection and grouping into different sigments so that it is easier to make recommendations and thus reducing to few columns.
  • For most of the missing values replaced with median values since I noticed from the data all these are right/left skewed.
  • ProdTaken is the dependent variable. About 18% are only taken. There is a huge opportunity for upsell.
  • Basic is the product which was taken by majority of the customers, not sure it is relatively effective one or promoted aggresively. Similar startegy could implement for the new product too.
  • Time for looking into the data and see if there is any support for assumptions/predictions.

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Summary of EDA¶

Data Description:¶

  • Dependent variable is 'ProdTaken' which is representing if the product wastaken or not by the customers.About 81% not taken and 19% were only taken.
  • There are missing values in the dataset.

Data Cleaning:¶

  • ID is a unique variable so it is dropped from the data.
  • All missing values were treated. Most of them are right/left skewed and hence replaced missing values with Median values for these columns - DurationOfPitch , DurationOfPitch, Age, NumberOfTrips, NumberOfChildrenVisiting, NumberOfFollowups, PreferredPropertyStar and TypeofContact
  • Gender has 'Fe Male' in few rows, it was treated properly.

Outliers¶

  • Found few outliers in MonthlyIncome (above 90k permonth salary, Age (above 60), Duration of the pitch (more than 100 seconds). This is reflecting the market conditions. Certain companies pay very high salraries depends on the nature of the job.
  • Data shows that there about 38 are above 60, all are making very good income, They tend to travel, in fact a good number to sell the new product (Wellness Tourism Package). Hence not treated them.
  • Duration of pitch - they are around 2 of them are above 100 seconds taken. Which is not un-common due to language issue or if they have many questions. Leaving the data as it is.

Observations from EDA:¶

  • Age is right skewed with meadian of 36 years
  • Monthly income is between 25-30K for most of the customers.
  • NumberOfTrips indicate all customers are willing to travel, in fact about 40% have been taking more than 3 trips in a year.
  • Number of followup shows if more times called, customers are inclind to take the product.
  • Duration of pitch also helping customers to make a decision.
  • Both PitchSatisfactionScore and ProductPitched have no significant impact.
  • Cusotmers who had passport taken different products more than who do not have.
  • Tier one city cusotmers taken products most.

Model evaluation criterion¶

The model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  • Predicting a Customer doesn't buy the new product but the customer bought
  • Predicting a customer purchase a new product, and the person doesn't purchase - direct loss to the company

Which case is more important?¶

  • Predicting a customer purchase a new product, and the person doesn't purchase

Which metric to optimize?¶

  • Recall to be maximized, the greater the Recall higher the chances of minimizing false negatives because if a model predicts that a person does purchase new product, in reality, that customer doesn't purchase, it is a direct loss to the company. So we need to build model which should identify customers who really not interested in purchasing the product.
  • Defining a function to provide recall scores on the train and test set and a function to show confusion matrix and used same code across the project.
In [65]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [66]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

}

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

  • Out of all the models tuned XGBoost is giving the decent performance though it is slightly overfitted the test data.
  • The model gives passport, product pitched, citytier and marital status are important features.
  • I'm not convinced that why passport is an important feature and came as number1 feature. When I look back data who ever having the passport those bought the product too. May be that was the reason. But I'm not sure.
  • Citytier 1 also bought products, which makes sense. Tier1 living customers obviously have good facilities and they give more importance to their well-being.
  • Product pitched (basic) Like I suggested if company offers the new product to this signment of customers, there are high chances of selleing it. Perhaps my recommendation is company could bundle the new product with this and offer to the existing customers. Either company should offer incentive/discount to attract this sigment of customers.
  • Marital status is also another key feature that should be consider , there are about 2500 customers in this sigment, a wide scope to sell the new product.
  • To my surprise Monthly_income is not in top 5. Most of the customers making good salray and above 25K (75%). Obvisouly if they make good monthly income they tend to spend on varity of items including on their own health.
  • My recommendation is if they target right customers who live in tier1 and tier2 cities, having decent income, who already bought basic package, not married. I'm sure company could sell the new product quite convincingly to these customers.
